english:
  title: Record of the Bamboo Pavilion at Former Inspector Kim's Residence
  author: Yu Bang-seon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The soil of Yeongcheon favors bamboo. Nearly every household cultivates it there—some fashioning it into pavilions and gazebos, others into hedges and fences. The whole county is much the same. Yet few truly understand what bamboo is meant to be.

    Former Inspector Kim Young-ji is a man of scholarly lineage who has loved bamboo since youth. After his retirement from office, he withdrew to his native hills, seeking neither renown nor advancement. He chose a plot of land south of the Two Waters and built a small pavilion east of his bedchamber. There he planted bamboo beside the structure, making it a place of peaceful rest, and named it the Bamboo Pavilion.

    Bamboo is a thing that passes through all four seasons unchanged, that transcends a hundred grasses and stands alone in its constancy. Its straightness heals the corruption of the vulgar; its strength stirs the indolent to vigor. In winter, its cold voice scatters like snow upon the window. In summer, its cool breath fills the mat. Through mist and haze, it summons visions of the Xiao and Xiang rivers before one's eyes. Under starlight and moonbeams, it transforms the chamber into a celestial realm where spirit and substance merge. When one recites poetry there, inspiration deepens; when guests arrive, conversation rises to greater clarity. All this the Bamboo Pavilion bestows.

    The world cherishes peach and plum blossoms in spring, lotus flowers in summer, chrysanthemums in autumn, and plum blossoms in winter. Yet bamboo is often overlooked. Peach and lotus adorned in floral splendor suit the wealthy; chrysanthemum and plum blossom equally as flowers draw the poet's praise. But who perceives that bamboo—straight yet unadorned, austere yet unstained by vulgarity, unchanging through heat and cold, the same hue through ancient and modern times—cannot be abandoned even for a moment when truly observed?

    Most people love merely the beauty of form and the fragrance of dew-kissed blossoms, unaware that these secretly incite the heart toward excess and sow seeds of corruption, leading one into dissolution and depravity. But bamboo is otherwise. To see it dispels meanness; to emulate it refines conduct. Rain and dew cannot enhance its splendor; wind and frost cannot alter its integrity. It lacks the dazzling hues of crimson and violet, the intoxicating fragrance—and so few know to love it.

    Consider the small man dealing with people: he beautifies his face, accommodates their words, presents himself as warm and yielding—thus many attach themselves to him. The superior man, conversely, keeps his conduct righteous, his bearing dignified, his aspect dignified—thus few seek him out. So it is with bamboo: it is little beloved.

    That Kim alone has come to love and cultivate it beside his dwelling, facing it day and night, reciting the movements of his own nature while washing away all that is base—his inner clarity must already be established. Surely he shall follow bamboo's example: serving his lord without wavering in loyalty, serving his parents without wavering in filial piety, maintaining his principles whether the state prospers or declines. He knows deeply why bamboo deserves to be loved, and he loves it truly.

    During my own southern exile, I was fortunate to visit and greatly admired it. Though my writing is crude, I have composed this record to hang upon his pavilion.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Xiao and Xiang rivers in Hunan Province were celebrated in classical Chinese literature for their misty, melancholic beauty—a common poetic allusion suggesting contemplative serenity.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Two Waters' (二水) refers to local geographical features near Yeongcheon, marking the site of Inspector Kim's chosen retreat.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of 'crimson and violet' (紅紫) represents the flashy, seductive beauty that the author argues leads toward moral corruption—a Confucian critique of superficial aesthetic pleasure.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between the 'small man' (小人) and the 'superior man' (君子) reflects Confucian moral philosophy, where virtue may appear less attractive than vice but possesses enduring integrity.
